WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.160 --> 00:00:04.970
&gt;&gt; Speaker 1: From the Library
of Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:16.470 --> 00:00:17.770
&gt;&gt; Sally Van de Water:
Hi, good afternoon,

00:00:17.770 --> 00:00:19.600
I'm Sally Van de Water
from the Folk Arts Program

00:00:19.600 --> 00:00:20.900
in Pennsylvania.

00:00:20.900 --> 00:00:22.200
It's my very great
pleasure to be here

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:24.690
at the American Folklife
Center and introducing

00:00:24.690 --> 00:00:27.290
to you the founder of the
Sattriya Dance Company,

00:00:27.290 --> 00:00:33.100
Madhusmita Bora and three of
the dancing monks of Assam.

00:00:33.100 --> 00:00:35.020
Thank you for being
here with us.

00:00:35.020 --> 00:00:36.870
Mandhu, I think I'd
like to start with you

00:00:36.870 --> 00:00:39.970
and ask you, what is Sattriya?

00:00:39.970 --> 00:00:41.610
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora:
It's a dance tradition

00:00:41.610 --> 00:00:44.250
from the remote northeast
corner of India,

00:00:44.250 --> 00:00:47.020
from the state called Assam.

00:00:47.020 --> 00:00:55.870
And it was preserved, nourished,
and created as a form of worship

00:00:55.870 --> 00:00:59.110
in the Hindu Vishnu Monasteries.

00:00:59.110 --> 00:01:05.890
It kind of stayed within the
Monastic walls for centuries.

00:01:05.890 --> 00:01:11.110
And it was only in the
mid-20th century that y,

00:01:11.110 --> 00:01:14.110
it started coming
out into the open.

00:01:14.110 --> 00:01:18.920
And today, it is one of India's
eight classical dance form.

00:01:18.920 --> 00:01:22.430
And that recognition
was actually recorded

00:01:22.430 --> 00:01:25.550
in the year 20000 And since
then it has catapulted

00:01:25.550 --> 00:01:27.440
into the proscenium stage
and you're seeing more

00:01:27.440 --> 00:01:31.930
and more people performing
and learning the dance.

00:01:31.930 --> 00:01:33.800
&gt;&gt; Sally Van de Water: How
is the dance different from,

00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:37.090
for example, Bharatanatyam, or
Kuchipudi, or do you see some

00:01:37.090 --> 00:01:39.550
of the other dances that
people might be familiar with.

00:01:39.550 --> 00:01:42.770
Also, it's an unbroken tradition
of more than 500 years.

00:01:42.770 --> 00:01:44.360
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora: It
is a living tradition.

00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:49.170
And this is the only dance form
that survived for centuries

00:01:49.170 --> 00:01:51.700
as a form of oral
tradition was passed

00:01:51.700 --> 00:01:55.140
on from one generation
of Hmong to the next.

00:01:55.140 --> 00:01:57.190
So, that is one major
difference.

00:01:57.190 --> 00:02:00.880
And it's a breathing,
living artform.

00:02:00.880 --> 00:02:02.910
And there are a lot
of similarities.

00:02:02.910 --> 00:02:05.510
And I will defer that
question to my teacher.

00:02:05.510 --> 00:02:20.110
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

00:02:20.110 --> 00:02:22.040
&gt;&gt; Prerona Bhuyan: So, we
have a lot of similarities,

00:02:22.040 --> 00:02:25.370
at the same times we have the
different see Hmong has the

00:02:25.370 --> 00:02:27.950
different dance [inaudible]
of India.

00:02:27.950 --> 00:02:35.720
And Sattriya, basically,
we use some elements

00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:40.960
as what we don't see in other
dance form, the example,

00:02:42.190 --> 00:02:45.450
we used the hand
gestures as a language.

00:02:45.450 --> 00:02:51.920
And in then classical dance and
this dance we call language.

00:02:51.920 --> 00:03:00.850
So separate, these hand
gestures, we use only Sattriya,

00:03:00.850 --> 00:03:04.880
but we don't see in other
classical dance of India.

00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:08.030
So, this is specific.

00:03:08.030 --> 00:03:15.240
Likewise we have some
elements like we bouncing.

00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:22.310
But we don't see in other
dance form of India.

00:03:22.310 --> 00:03:25.750
Only we can see in
Manipuri dance.

00:03:25.750 --> 00:03:27.430
Because Manipuri is
very near to use,

00:03:27.430 --> 00:03:32.210
and it was the same
stays in the long times.

00:03:32.210 --> 00:03:34.720
But after that it was separate.

00:03:34.720 --> 00:03:37.700
So, we can see only
Manipuri dance.

00:03:37.700 --> 00:03:44.760
So, we have a lot of difference,
then also the language.

00:03:44.760 --> 00:03:48.070
And we use the Brazowvi
[phonic] language.

00:03:48.070 --> 00:03:50.010
This language composed

00:03:50.010 --> 00:03:54.810
by our great saint [foreign
name] in 15th century.

00:03:54.810 --> 00:03:59.470
This language is what
kind of mixed language.

00:03:59.470 --> 00:04:06.900
And he used this language as
a holy language because at

00:04:06.900 --> 00:04:11.250
that time he has to
convince to the people,

00:04:11.250 --> 00:04:16.580
if he used a normal language

00:04:16.580 --> 00:04:20.630
like ordinary people
used common language,

00:04:20.630 --> 00:04:25.810
the people don't believe that
this is one kind of holy.

00:04:25.810 --> 00:04:28.880
So, because of that he
used a mixed language.

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:31.120
So, this is called
Brazowvi language.

00:04:31.120 --> 00:04:35.060
So, in Sattriya, we
use this language.

00:04:35.060 --> 00:04:39.010
So, we have a lot
of differences.

00:04:39.010 --> 00:04:40.310
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora:
Also, you know,

00:04:40.310 --> 00:04:44.650
it's mostly Krishna worship,
we don't have too many,

00:04:44.650 --> 00:04:48.100
I mean goddesses, when
we're telling stories.

00:04:48.100 --> 00:04:50.870
Most of the stories
are related to Krishna.

00:04:50.870 --> 00:04:53.210
And the principle
emotion is [foreign word].

00:04:53.210 --> 00:04:56.640
&gt;&gt; Prerona Bhuyan: Yeah,
that is very important piece

00:04:56.640 --> 00:05:02.040
in Sattriya, because Sattriya,
they take it to the devotion.

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:07.050
So, because of that,
yes, it was the nine kind

00:05:07.050 --> 00:05:09.770
of [foreign word],
the sentiments.

00:05:09.770 --> 00:05:17.390
But our ultimate
destination we have search,

00:05:17.390 --> 00:05:23.000
we have to find the [foreign
word], this devotion.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:26.780
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora: So, yeah,
it's a very devotional artform.

00:05:26.780 --> 00:05:28.330
Because it's part
of your worship.

00:05:28.330 --> 00:05:32.280
And it's always, you know,
it ends with submission

00:05:32.280 --> 00:05:34.180
to the lord and the universe.

00:05:34.180 --> 00:05:35.480
&gt;&gt; Sally Van de Water:
You begin with devotion

00:05:35.480 --> 00:05:38.320
and then there's music,
and then there's dance

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:40.130
and then you end with devotion.

00:05:40.130 --> 00:05:41.430
That's lovely.

00:05:41.430 --> 00:05:44.830
As part of today's performance,

00:05:44.830 --> 00:05:51.190
you did your final piece was
invoking 10 the incarnations

00:05:51.190 --> 00:05:52.490
of Krishna.

00:05:52.490 --> 00:05:53.790
Can you talk a little
bit about how you

00:05:53.790 --> 00:05:58.800
and your dance partner portrayed
that, how you were able to make

00:05:58.800 --> 00:06:02.040
that come alive for the
audience through dance?

00:06:02.040 --> 00:06:04.120
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora: So, in our
tradition there are actually,

00:06:04.120 --> 00:06:05.940
you know, the other
Indian classical dance,

00:06:05.940 --> 00:06:07.790
there's also another difference,

00:06:07.790 --> 00:06:12.740
there are 10 primary
incarnations, in ours we say 24.

00:06:12.740 --> 00:06:16.430
But we still pick 10,
the 10 primary ones.

00:06:16.430 --> 00:06:18.790
And you know, we
talk about them.

00:06:18.790 --> 00:06:24.040
And the piece that we did, we
don't know who choreographed it,

00:06:24.040 --> 00:06:26.580
but it is very, very old.

00:06:26.580 --> 00:06:28.740
And you know [foreign
name] taught us

00:06:28.740 --> 00:06:31.820
and that was actually
thanks to a grant

00:06:31.820 --> 00:06:35.080
from the Pennsylvania
Council on the Arts.

00:06:35.080 --> 00:06:38.930
So, how we did it was we
just divided our roles,

00:06:38.930 --> 00:06:41.190
the way it was choreographed.

00:06:41.190 --> 00:06:43.560
So, when, you know she's
portraying the fish,

00:06:43.560 --> 00:06:45.480
I become the water.

00:06:45.480 --> 00:06:47.210
Or when, you know,
she's a turtle head,

00:06:47.210 --> 00:06:48.530
I'm the turtle shell, you know.

00:06:48.530 --> 00:06:49.910
&gt;&gt; Sally Van de Water: Because
she's portraying Krishna,

00:06:49.910 --> 00:06:52.300
and you're portraying
Krishna nemesis.

00:06:52.300 --> 00:06:53.640
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora: And
then, just because you know,

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:54.940
she's in a male costume.

00:06:54.940 --> 00:06:58.590
So, that's the other interesting
aspect of this dance form.

00:06:58.590 --> 00:07:00.920
It's very gender fluid.

00:07:00.920 --> 00:07:04.820
Because the Hmong
dress up as women.

00:07:04.820 --> 00:07:08.330
So, probably it is the
only dance form right now,

00:07:08.330 --> 00:07:12.510
where women also dress
up in a man costume.

00:07:12.510 --> 00:07:17.040
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:19.830
Kuchipudi, in Kuchipudi
they do it But in Kuchipudi,

00:07:19.830 --> 00:07:22.830
I don't know, do females
dress up as men, anymore?

00:07:22.830 --> 00:07:24.350
I don't see that.

00:07:24.350 --> 00:07:27.820
I know male can dress as female,
but female dressing up as men,

00:07:27.820 --> 00:07:31.150
I think this is the only
dance form that have it?

00:07:31.150 --> 00:07:35.130
&gt;&gt; Prerona Bhuyan: Yes, but
we have to think about this.

00:07:35.130 --> 00:07:38.900
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora: Yeah,
so that is one of you know

00:07:38.900 --> 00:07:42.750
so because she is
always in the turban,

00:07:42.750 --> 00:07:44.520
so she gets to play
the good guy,

00:07:44.520 --> 00:07:46.330
and I essentially
become the bad guy.

00:07:46.330 --> 00:07:48.790
&gt;&gt; Prerona Bhuyan: And we don't
say that this is the dance

00:07:48.790 --> 00:07:50.630
of Krishna, because
we only believe

00:07:50.630 --> 00:07:53.890
that Krishna, Krishna
[inaudible].

00:07:53.890 --> 00:07:57.330
So, we don't believe
the other goddesses.

00:07:57.330 --> 00:08:00.520
But yes, we believe we respect.

00:08:00.520 --> 00:08:06.880
But we believe this is a part of
the Krishna so, because of that.

00:08:06.880 --> 00:08:13.550
The other classical dance form,
when they dance, they dedicate

00:08:13.550 --> 00:08:15.820
to the dance for the goddess.

00:08:15.820 --> 00:08:18.850
We dedicate it only for Krishna.

00:08:18.850 --> 00:08:21.110
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora: Yeah,
Krishna is the principle deity.

00:08:21.110 --> 00:08:22.410
And that also brings

00:08:22.410 --> 00:08:25.340
to the other difference
you're talking about.

00:08:25.340 --> 00:08:28.240
Our [foreign word] is called
[foreign word], it's very soft.

00:08:28.240 --> 00:08:32.660
It's unlike the other dance form
where it's very, very rigorous.

00:08:32.660 --> 00:08:35.780
There's the bouncing
that you see.

00:08:35.780 --> 00:08:39.640
And that almost like the flowy
movement of the river, I think,

00:08:39.640 --> 00:08:42.170
you know you're kind of
gliding on the stage,

00:08:42.170 --> 00:08:44.910
rather than standing and making.

00:08:44.910 --> 00:08:46.210
&gt;&gt; Sally Van de Water: Well,

00:08:46.210 --> 00:08:48.620
it's incredibly elegant
and fluid, yes.

00:08:48.620 --> 00:08:49.920
Absolutely.

00:08:49.920 --> 00:08:51.620
&gt;&gt; Prerona Bhuyan:
Yes, because we believe

00:08:51.620 --> 00:08:57.460
that it is the [inaudible]
to a heart for mother earth.

00:08:57.460 --> 00:09:01.070
So, because of that we bounce.

00:09:01.070 --> 00:09:04.610
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora: Whereas,
the other dance form, the bow

00:09:04.610 --> 00:09:08.540
and then they stamp on the
mother earth [laughter].

00:09:08.540 --> 00:09:09.840
&gt;&gt; Sally Van de Water:
Well, I think,

00:09:09.840 --> 00:09:11.750
you know it's really remarkable
that Sattriya has more

00:09:11.750 --> 00:09:15.440
than 500 years of unbroken
tradition that's always been

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:17.490
carried on in the
monastery except

00:09:17.490 --> 00:09:20.630
in the last, say 20 years or so.

00:09:20.630 --> 00:09:22.000
Women are now also
doing this as well.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:23.580
Can you talk a little
bit more about that,

00:09:23.580 --> 00:09:25.080
you're one of the
first women to do?

00:09:25.080 --> 00:09:26.380
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora: No,
I'm not one of the first.

00:09:26.380 --> 00:09:27.680
&gt;&gt; Sally Van de Water:
Oh, you're not.

00:09:27.680 --> 00:09:28.980
Okay, sorry.

00:09:28.980 --> 00:09:34.510
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora: So,
actually probably 1960s.

00:09:34.510 --> 00:09:40.290
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

00:09:40.290 --> 00:09:45.930
Probavly 1960, but it was not,
you know, it was not very,

00:09:45.930 --> 00:09:47.820
for the lack of a better
word, it was not very cool.

00:09:47.820 --> 00:09:49.310
There was not enough funding.

00:09:49.310 --> 00:09:52.470
And there were other dance,
classical art forms that were

00:09:52.470 --> 00:09:55.110
so vibrant at that
time, even in Assam.

00:09:55.110 --> 00:09:56.410
Like [inaudible].

00:09:56.410 --> 00:09:58.410
So, people were more
drawn toward that.

00:09:58.410 --> 00:10:00.100
You know,

00:10:00.100 --> 00:10:01.400
so there were like two,

00:10:01.400 --> 00:10:02.700
three practitioners,
but not very many.

00:10:02.700 --> 00:10:06.510
The access to the
artform was also hard.

00:10:06.510 --> 00:10:12.170
Because most of the Hmong
were not allowed to teach.

00:10:12.170 --> 00:10:14.320
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

00:10:14.320 --> 00:10:16.860
So, you know one of my
teachers [foreign name] was,

00:10:16.860 --> 00:10:19.630
I mean he nearly
got excommunicated

00:10:19.630 --> 00:10:22.020
because he ventured out
to teach at that point.

00:10:22.020 --> 00:10:25.510
You know, this was in the 1980s.

00:10:25.510 --> 00:10:31.190
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

00:10:31.190 --> 00:10:33.880
So, he also wanted to
like teach outside.

00:10:33.880 --> 00:10:35.520
But it was, you know
there was this resistance,

00:10:35.520 --> 00:10:37.930
because the older monks wanted
to preserve the tradition,

00:10:37.930 --> 00:10:41.070
and to let go was
really , really hard.

00:10:41.070 --> 00:10:44.730
But I think since
2000, it has become.

00:10:44.730 --> 00:10:46.840
You know it has become
more accessible.

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:50.100
A lot of things have happened.

00:10:50.100 --> 00:10:53.950
Of course, India has
progressed by leaps and bounds.

00:10:53.950 --> 00:10:55.700
Transportation is easier,

00:10:55.700 --> 00:10:58.230
the island is more
accessible to go and learn.

00:10:58.230 --> 00:11:01.170
And then, you know there are
practitioners like Bhabananda

00:11:01.170 --> 00:11:03.870
who are actually moving
out and like, you know,

00:11:03.870 --> 00:11:07.870
staying in the cities and
teaching students from all over.

00:11:07.870 --> 00:11:12.030
&gt;&gt; Prerona Bhuyan: But I think,
this is my personal view,

00:11:12.030 --> 00:11:15.880
that the [inaudible] it not mean
the [inaudible] didn't allow.

00:11:15.880 --> 00:11:19.290
It means the outsiders
not interested about this.

00:11:19.290 --> 00:11:23.500
So, when the outsider
interest to know about this,

00:11:23.500 --> 00:11:25.640
that's first of most often.

00:11:25.640 --> 00:11:30.680
Because the should trust
people outside and they teach

00:11:30.680 --> 00:11:32.860
for the women insiders.

00:11:32.860 --> 00:11:37.300
So, I think that outsider
was not interested before.

00:11:37.300 --> 00:11:42.910
So, when the outsiders
get interested about this,

00:11:42.910 --> 00:11:48.440
the [inaudible] people, they
wanted to give them these.

00:11:48.440 --> 00:11:50.690
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora: So, yeah,
it was more like access.

00:11:50.690 --> 00:11:51.990
You know there was no access.

00:11:51.990 --> 00:11:53.530
So, yeah that must
have brought them yeah.

00:11:53.530 --> 00:11:54.830
&gt;&gt; Sally Van de Water:
Absolutely.

00:11:54.830 --> 00:12:00.630
Can I ask you, Mr. [inaudible]
how has it been to work

00:12:00.630 --> 00:12:03.630
with Madhu, you've been
her apprenticeship teacher

00:12:03.630 --> 00:12:05.320
for a couple of years now?

00:12:05.320 --> 00:12:08.280
How has that been for you

00:12:08.280 --> 00:12:11.510
to have a student in
the United States.

00:12:11.510 --> 00:12:21.590
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

00:12:21.590 --> 00:12:23.740
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora: So, both
of them actually I trained

00:12:23.740 --> 00:12:26.670
under both of them
around the same time,

00:12:26.670 --> 00:12:29.510
so they can both
talk about that.

00:12:29.510 --> 00:13:04.320
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

00:13:04.320 --> 00:13:06.510
So, he says when he
first joined the.

00:13:06.510 --> 00:13:10.040
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

00:13:10.040 --> 00:13:11.630
When he was five, most of them,

00:13:11.630 --> 00:13:14.870
Barbayan is seventh generation
Hmong from his family.

