me you have to wait for an hour.

00:15:42.610 --> 00:15:47.070
And then, you know after waiting
around when I finally met

00:15:47.070 --> 00:15:49.350
with him, he said; you know,
I told him that I wanted

00:15:49.350 --> 00:15:51.010
to learn the dance form.

00:15:51.010 --> 00:15:53.300
And you know, he said
he was very happy

00:15:53.300 --> 00:15:54.830
because he likes teaching

00:15:54.830 --> 00:15:58.710
and then he knew I
had come from so far.

00:15:58.710 --> 00:16:02.510
So, he happily took
me under his wings.

00:16:02.510 --> 00:16:32.050
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

00:16:32.050 --> 00:16:34.840
So, it was in 2002,
he's getting emotional.

00:16:34.840 --> 00:16:39.690
So, this was in 2002 when
you know we started talking.

00:16:39.690 --> 00:16:41.940
And then, you know we would
always have these discussions.

00:16:41.940 --> 00:16:44.870
And I always said I
wanted to bring them here,

00:16:44.870 --> 00:16:48.290
and he would say, yeah can
we all go and maybe someday;

00:16:48.290 --> 00:16:51.450
because they have never
been to the United States.

00:16:51.450 --> 00:16:56.080
And he said, you know maybe
somehow you can arrange it.

00:16:56.080 --> 00:16:58.550
And you know we knew it
was a Herculean task.

00:16:58.550 --> 00:17:00.480
Because bringing
a group of people

00:17:00.480 --> 00:17:04.940
when you know the funding,
it is very expensive.

00:17:04.940 --> 00:17:07.130
And, but you know
he always believed.

00:17:07.130 --> 00:17:09.390
I mean he would always say, it
will happen, it will happen.

00:17:09.390 --> 00:17:11.700
And I also had this crazy dream.

00:17:11.700 --> 00:17:14.280
So, he said he is so
happy to be here today.

00:17:14.280 --> 00:17:17.480
He is overcome with emotions,
because this has been,

00:17:17.480 --> 00:17:20.470
you know we've talked about
this since the early 2000s

00:17:20.470 --> 00:17:23.260
and it's happening and
it's like really unreal.

00:17:23.260 --> 00:17:24.560
&gt;&gt; Sally Van de Water: Well,

00:17:24.560 --> 00:17:25.860
it's really a very
great honor, thank you.

00:17:25.860 --> 00:17:29.540
We're very honored to have you
here in this magnificent space.

00:17:29.540 --> 00:17:31.440
Thank you, I hope that you
have a wonderful time here

00:17:31.440 --> 00:17:32.820
in the United States.

00:17:32.820 --> 00:17:34.300
Thank you.

00:17:34.300 --> 00:17:40.090
I have a blank moment now.

00:17:40.090 --> 00:17:43.090
What else do you
think is important?

00:17:43.090 --> 00:17:48.890
What else is important for
you that we record with.

00:17:48.890 --> 00:17:54.510
Do you want to ask
[inaudible] about?

00:17:54.510 --> 00:19:08.500
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

00:19:08.500 --> 00:19:10.020
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora: So,
he was five years old

00:19:10.020 --> 00:19:11.320
when he joined the
[foreign word].

00:19:11.320 --> 00:19:12.620
And they're cousins.

00:19:12.620 --> 00:19:15.440
And they're both National
Award winners, both of them.

00:19:15.440 --> 00:19:19.570
So, you know and for 18
years he trained vigorously

00:19:19.570 --> 00:19:22.130
in the artform because he
lived in the monastery.

00:19:22.130 --> 00:19:23.800
But this was, you know prior

00:19:23.800 --> 00:19:27.100
to Hotchia [phonic]
becoming a classical artform.

00:19:27.100 --> 00:19:30.630
He really wanted to study
another classical dance form

00:19:30.630 --> 00:19:34.110
to bring those rigors
into his movement.

00:19:34.110 --> 00:19:40.310
So, he left the monastery in
pursuit of studies and trained

00:19:40.310 --> 00:19:42.720
in another dance
form for two years,

00:19:42.720 --> 00:19:44.210
but he doesn't perform
it or teach it.

00:19:44.210 --> 00:19:47.390
It was just for his own
understanding, and you know,

00:19:47.390 --> 00:19:50.310
studying Hotchia as
a classical artform.

00:19:50.310 --> 00:19:53.870
And then, because he was
originally from the monastery.

00:19:53.870 --> 00:19:55.170
So, there are a lot of,

00:19:55.170 --> 00:19:57.250
they have to live a
very disciplined life.

00:19:57.250 --> 00:19:58.550
It is hard.

00:19:58.550 --> 00:19:59.850
Bhabananda manages.

00:19:59.850 --> 00:20:01.150
I don't know how.

00:20:01.150 --> 00:20:03.890
But it is very, very hard.

00:20:03.890 --> 00:20:06.980
So, when he was there, you
know he started living,

00:20:06.980 --> 00:20:08.280
and now he's a family man.

00:20:08.280 --> 00:20:09.660
He kind of left the order.

00:20:09.660 --> 00:20:12.770
And for me, again the access

00:20:12.770 --> 00:20:16.860
to Madgule has always been an
issue, because it is you know,

00:20:16.860 --> 00:20:18.570
you have to travel by boat.

00:20:18.570 --> 00:20:20.660
When the river is in
state, it's really,

00:20:20.660 --> 00:20:22.940
really hard to get there.

00:20:22.940 --> 00:20:27.640
So, I was also looking for
alternatives in the city.

00:20:27.640 --> 00:20:29.110
So, I would divide my time.

00:20:29.110 --> 00:20:31.620
I could only go to Madgule for
some time, and then when I'm

00:20:31.620 --> 00:20:34.090
in the city, where my
parents are right now.

00:20:34.090 --> 00:20:36.240
And [inaudible] kind
of lives there.

00:20:36.240 --> 00:20:40.800
And again, the head of the
monastery connected us and said,

00:20:40.800 --> 00:20:43.090
you know when you're in
town, in your hometown,

00:20:43.090 --> 00:20:44.390
you can study under him.

00:20:44.390 --> 00:20:46.950
So, that's how we did it.

00:20:46.950 --> 00:20:50.340
&gt;&gt; Sally Van de Water:
Tell me more about Assam.

00:20:50.340 --> 00:20:52.140
You grew up there.

00:20:52.140 --> 00:20:55.450
And you grew up in the
town and how far is

00:20:55.450 --> 00:20:57.240
that from Madgule
from the monastery?

00:20:57.240 --> 00:20:58.540
The town?

00:20:58.540 --> 00:20:59.840
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora:
It is pretty far.

00:20:59.840 --> 00:21:06.540
So, I was born in a
small down called Dispur

00:21:06.540 --> 00:21:08.990
and then I was raised mostly

00:21:08.990 --> 00:21:12.480
in my father's village it's
called Madhcal [phonic].

00:21:12.480 --> 00:21:17.390
And it's interesting because
Madhcal is kind of a seat of art

00:21:17.390 --> 00:21:20.110
and culture, so I
grew up like listening

00:21:20.110 --> 00:21:23.860
to the rhythms of
you know Hotchia.

00:21:23.860 --> 00:21:27.520
My aunts and uncles
trained in it.

00:21:27.520 --> 00:21:29.960
and we have this
unbroken tradition

00:21:29.960 --> 00:21:33.080
which is hundred-something
years old.

00:21:33.080 --> 00:21:35.140
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

00:21:35.140 --> 00:21:36.440
That happens in my village.

00:21:36.440 --> 00:21:37.740
So, all my cousins.

00:21:37.740 --> 00:21:39.750
I mean it happened this year,
and I was supposed to perform,

00:21:39.750 --> 00:21:41.680
but I couldn't make it.

00:21:41.680 --> 00:21:44.370
My uncles, my extended
family were always involved

00:21:44.370 --> 00:21:45.670
in [foreign word].

00:21:45.670 --> 00:21:49.270
So, you know it was kind of
second nature almost to kind

00:21:49.270 --> 00:21:51.730
of get immersed in the arts.

00:21:51.730 --> 00:21:58.930
But Madgule is pretty
far from there and then,

00:21:58.930 --> 00:22:04.430
I had to pursue my
education and at that time,

00:22:04.430 --> 00:22:06.500
Assam was in a very
turbulent state.

00:22:06.500 --> 00:22:08.710
You know, we had a
secessionist outfit.

00:22:08.710 --> 00:22:11.880
So, it was not a very safe
place for most people.

00:22:11.880 --> 00:22:16.250
So, my parents kind of
encouraged me to leave the state

00:22:16.250 --> 00:22:20.330
and go outside for my high
school and my college.

00:22:20.330 --> 00:22:22.080
And that's what I did.

00:22:22.080 --> 00:22:26.020
So, you know there was,
I learned under a teacher

00:22:26.020 --> 00:22:29.010
in my hometown for
a little while,

00:22:29.010 --> 00:22:33.580
and then that connection
was snapped because.

00:22:33.580 --> 00:22:37.430
Yeah. And that was, and I
was four or five years old,

00:22:37.430 --> 00:22:40.630
until about seven years of age.

00:22:40.630 --> 00:22:43.410
Then I left Dispur
and I left [inaudible]

00:22:43.410 --> 00:22:45.790
and I kind of grew up in Delhi.

00:22:45.790 --> 00:22:48.790
And there was no, you
know I didn't have access

00:22:48.790 --> 00:22:50.090
to anybody then.

00:22:50.090 --> 00:22:56.850
So, I went to the next best
alternative, which was Kathak.

00:22:56.850 --> 00:22:59.710
So, I trained in Kathak
for about 16 years.

00:22:59.710 --> 00:23:04.260
But what was interesting
was my Kathak teacher,

00:23:04.260 --> 00:23:07.490
Janet Kadidi [assumed spelling],
who lives in New York.

00:23:07.490 --> 00:23:11.410
And she has trained under
one of the luminaries,

00:23:11.410 --> 00:23:12.710
a living legend [inaudible].

00:23:12.710 --> 00:23:16.530
And I joined her dance company.

00:23:16.530 --> 00:23:18.320
So, I was part of
the Kathak Ensemble

00:23:18.320 --> 00:23:19.810
and Friends in New York.

00:23:19.810 --> 00:23:23.540
And it was very interesting
because in doing choreographies,

00:23:23.540 --> 00:23:26.040
or when I'm dancing, and
she would say, you're lost,

00:23:26.040 --> 00:23:28.500
she'll always say, there's
some sadness in your movement.

00:23:28.500 --> 00:23:30.380
And where did you get this from.

00:23:30.380 --> 00:23:32.400
And it was my muscle memory.

00:23:32.400 --> 00:23:36.070
So, even though I was one of
the senior most performers

00:23:36.070 --> 00:23:39.160
in her group, you know
one day she just said,

00:23:39.160 --> 00:23:40.460
child you need to go.

00:23:40.460 --> 00:23:42.950
You need to go back, and
you know follow your heart,

00:23:42.950 --> 00:23:44.410
this is not where your heart is.

00:23:44.410 --> 00:23:49.570
And I think, you know
even to this day for me,

00:23:49.570 --> 00:23:54.360
like she is my ultimate
teacher, because she let go.

00:23:54.360 --> 00:23:56.930
And she said, just go, and
follow your dreams, you know

00:23:56.930 --> 00:23:59.380
and pursue your passion.

00:23:59.380 --> 00:24:03.030
So, that's how I actually
ended up in the monastery

00:24:03.030 --> 00:24:07.500
when I met [inaudible]
the first time.

00:24:07.500 --> 00:24:12.310
And then, you know I realized
because it's so precious

00:24:12.310 --> 00:24:15.530
and it's of course, you know
there was this deep connection.

00:24:15.530 --> 00:24:18.440
It was very easy
to get back to it.

00:24:18.440 --> 00:24:24.390
And I let go of Kathak even
after 16 years of training,

00:24:24.390 --> 00:24:27.110
I gave away my bells,
all my costumes,

00:24:27.110 --> 00:24:29.300
because I didn't want any kind

00:24:29.300 --> 00:24:32.630
of you know alteration
of what I'm doing.

00:24:32.630 --> 00:24:35.050
Because this is my
heritage and I would

00:24:35.050 --> 00:24:41.240
like to preserve it the way, and
you know accord it the respect

00:24:41.240 --> 00:24:42.540
and sanctity that it deserves.

00:24:42.540 --> 00:24:43.840
&gt;&gt; Sally Van de Water:
That's wonderful.

00:24:43.840 --> 00:24:45.140
I know you've got
a lot of support

00:24:45.140 --> 00:24:46.440
from the P Foundation and.

00:24:46.440 --> 00:24:48.540
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora:
Absolutely, I've been so lucky

00:24:48.540 --> 00:24:52.650
that you know, I
mean two PCA grants,

00:24:52.650 --> 00:24:55.330
three Levy Foundation
grants and in one of,

00:24:55.330 --> 00:24:58.250
the second Levy Foundation grant
Bhabananda was in the monastery

00:24:58.250 --> 00:25:02.630
and that's how, I was
working on this project, yeah.

00:25:02.630 --> 00:25:04.530
So, you know so Bhabananda kind

00:25:04.530 --> 00:25:08.860
of helped me document all the
basic grammar of the dance form.

00:25:08.860 --> 00:25:13.250
And Pew, I mean Pew
is unbelievable.

00:25:13.250 --> 00:25:16.730
You know, I just in my wildest
dreams did not think it was

00:25:16.730 --> 00:25:18.170
going to happen.

00:25:18.170 --> 00:25:22.710
And here we are you know
after a year of like,

00:25:22.710 --> 00:25:27.270
it feels like I have done a
PhD in the last year or two.

00:25:27.270 --> 00:25:32.650
But you know I'm so
grateful for the support.

00:25:32.650 --> 00:25:38.540
And yes Pew is you know very
generous with their grant,

00:25:38.540 --> 00:25:40.380
but leading up to it, you know

00:25:40.380 --> 00:25:42.480
if I wouldn't have
had the support Levy,

00:25:42.480 --> 00:25:45.230
or from Pennsylvania
Council on the Arts,

00:25:45.230 --> 00:25:49.280
I don't think I'd
be where I am today.

00:25:49.280 --> 00:25:52.990
Because it's a very lonely ride.

00:25:52.990 --> 00:25:56.500
You know, since I'm the
only one practicing it here

00:25:56.500 --> 00:26:02.320
and that access to the teachers
and to the nerve center is

00:26:02.320 --> 00:26:04.340
so important and without
funding and support,

00:26:04.340 --> 00:26:06.210
you know I wouldn't
have been able

00:26:06.210 --> 00:26:07.850
to do what I'm doing right now.

00:26:07.850 --> 00:26:09.150
&gt;&gt; Sally Van de Water:
I really want

00:26:09.150 --> 00:26:10.450
to ask you a little
bit more about that.

00:26:10.450 --> 00:26:12.500
You are the only
practitioner here

00:26:12.500 --> 00:26:15.830
in the United States doing this
artform, and it's usually done

00:26:15.830 --> 00:26:18.750
in the context of a
group, a larger group

00:26:18.750 --> 00:26:20.060
such as at the monastery.

00:26:20.060 --> 00:26:21.680
How do you negotiate that?

00:26:21.680 --> 00:26:23.770
How do you?

00:26:23.770 --> 00:26:25.850
What's your daily practice like?

00:26:25.850 --> 00:26:29.260
What do you do to keep
the traditional alive

00:26:29.260 --> 00:26:32.320
in your own life?

00:26:32.320 --> 00:26:34.750
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora: I feel
like, you know for most of us,

00:26:34.750 --> 00:26:37.950
it becomes; it's the
nature of the artform.

00:26:37.950 --> 00:26:40.450
It is actually a way of life.

00:26:40.450 --> 00:26:41.750
It's a way of life.

00:26:41.750 --> 00:26:44.840
For them, of course, I mean
this is, they live, breathe

00:26:44.840 --> 00:26:47.300
and you know this
is what they do.

00:26:47.300 --> 00:26:49.560
But even for other
practitioners,

00:26:49.560 --> 00:26:53.130
I think it becomes
your life's philosophy.

00:26:53.130 --> 00:26:58.020
And it is hard like
to be the only person.

00:26:58.020 --> 00:27:01.020
But I've been very blessed
because my dance partner

00:27:01.020 --> 00:27:03.600
and you know the cofounder

00:27:03.600 --> 00:27:06.360
of the dance company
is my sister-in-law.

00:27:06.360 --> 00:27:08.480
Which is just, you
know was wonderful.

00:27:08.480 --> 00:27:09.960
That's very convenient.

00:27:09.960 --> 00:27:13.390
And she travels here quite
frequently whenever we have

00:27:13.390 --> 00:27:15.400
shows, big shows.

00:27:15.400 --> 00:27:19.570
And we dance together,
even in India,

00:27:19.570 --> 00:27:23.040
or last year we performed
in London.

00:27:23.040 --> 00:27:27.960
It is hard, because it is
essentially a community worship

00:27:27.960 --> 00:27:29.260
which they can do.

00:27:29.260 --> 00:27:30.840
I mean we cannot
create that music,

00:27:30.840 --> 00:27:32.370
you know I mean this
is very special.

00:27:32.370 --> 00:27:35.090
So, the first time that we're
doing it with live musicians,

00:27:35.090 --> 00:27:37.480
you know, yeah, I mean here.

00:27:37.480 --> 00:27:40.550
You know, because I don't
have access to that.

00:27:40.550 --> 00:27:42.270
So, this was very, very special

00:27:42.270 --> 00:27:44.650
because we're always
dancing to recorded music.

00:27:44.650 --> 00:27:48.840
So, even though, yes, you know
your philosophical and it's

00:27:48.840 --> 00:27:52.020
such a spiritual artform, and
you're in it and you're in it

00:27:52.020 --> 00:27:55.590
and you're you know, every
movement is sort of an offering

00:27:55.590 --> 00:27:57.420
to the universe and to the Lord.

00:27:57.420 --> 00:28:02.590
But like, it's not the same when
you don't have the community.

00:28:02.590 --> 00:28:05.520
You know. So, it
is very special.

00:28:05.520 --> 00:28:07.440
But like, to keep
it going, again,

00:28:07.440 --> 00:28:13.820
it's because I think it's
the passion that drives it.

00:28:13.820 --> 00:28:18.660
It's also like you know these
are the stories and you feel

00:28:18.660 --> 00:28:22.110
that burden to kind of carry
on these stories forward

00:28:22.110 --> 00:28:24.430
and leave it for
the next generation.

00:28:24.430 --> 00:28:25.730
For me, it's my son.

00:28:25.730 --> 00:28:28.800
You know, that's his
connection to his roots.

00:28:28.800 --> 00:28:30.370
So, that's what drives
me, I guess.

00:28:30.370 --> 00:28:31.680
&gt;&gt; Sally Van de Water:
Does he dance?

00:28:31.680 --> 00:28:33.230
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora: No,
he doesn't [laughter].

00:28:33.230 --> 00:28:34.870
But he's really into
all the stories.

00:28:34.870 --> 00:28:37.270
So, yeah.

00:28:37.270 --> 00:28:38.570
&gt;&gt; Sally Van de Water:
Well, thank you.

00:28:38.570 --> 00:28:39.870
We're so honored
to have you here.

00:28:39.870 --> 00:28:41.990
Thank you again, thank you
for traveling such a long way.

00:28:41.990 --> 00:28:43.290
Is there anything
else that you would

00:28:43.290 --> 00:28:45.810
like to say, or like to add?

00:28:45.810 --> 00:28:47.940
&gt;&gt; Madhusmita Bora: So,
what we're really excited

00:28:47.940 --> 00:28:55.780
about you know is the Pew
Grant is funding this project,

00:28:55.780 --> 00:28:57.340
which is called the
Threads of History,

00:28:57.340 --> 00:28:59.930
Resurrection of the Textile.

00:28:59.930 --> 00:29:04.810
So, this is you know a part
of tapestry that I discovered

00:29:04.810 --> 00:29:06.180
in the Philadelphia
Museum of Art,

00:29:06.180 --> 00:29:08.030
which was actually in storage.

00:29:08.030 --> 00:29:11.110
And on the trip when I met
Barbayan and [inaudible]

00:29:11.110 --> 00:29:14.450
and we were documenting
the grammar of the artform

00:29:14.450 --> 00:29:18.780
through my Levy Grant was when
he mentioned about, he said,

00:29:18.780 --> 00:29:20.080
you know there is a possibility,

00:29:20.080 --> 00:29:22.330
that you know this
tapestry exists.

00:29:22.330 --> 00:29:23.690
So, I was on a wild goose chase,

00:29:23.690 --> 00:29:27.460
through because I didn't know
how to ask them what it was,

00:29:27.460 --> 00:29:30.160
because I mean if I say [foreign
word] they had no idea what

00:29:30.160 --> 00:29:31.620
it was.

00:29:31.620 --> 00:29:37.340
So, it took about
almost 2, 3 years

00:29:37.340 --> 00:29:40.720
and by then the museum
had gotten funding

00:29:40.720 --> 00:29:42.140
to digitize their collection.

00:29:42.140 --> 00:29:45.200
So, one night I was looking
through their digital archives

00:29:45.200 --> 00:29:48.820
and I came across it and it was
called the clothe of Vrindavan.

00:29:48.820 --> 00:29:52.540
So, immediately, I was so
excited and I kind of called him

00:29:52.540 --> 00:29:54.710
and sent him the
pictures and I said,

00:29:54.710 --> 00:29:56.110
is this what we were
looking for.

00:29:56.110 --> 00:29:57.410
And he said, yes that's it.

00:29:57.410 --> 00:29:59.460
You know, incredible I know.

00:29:59.460 --> 00:30:01.170
